The Americans and Canadians in our group of 10 gasped and then laughed as our guide explained that guinea pigs are considered a good source of protein and were never kept as pets in Ecuador. In fact, when the missionaries came they painted murals of the Last Supper but put local foods on the table to help assimilate the locals into the Catholic religion. So Jesus and his disciples are shown eating corn, squash blossoms and whole roast guinea pig instead of the usual European fare.
Our guide in Quito seemed especially proud of how her ancient ancestors were able to “shrink” heads and gave a very detailed explanation of how it’s done. It’s best to listen to this on an empty stomach — especially when she brings out a real shrunken head.
AZCENTRAL
Zimbabwe safari: Four days of spotting hippos, giraffes and elephants
Our trip to Quito also included a trek to Mitad del Mundo, also known as the equator. At the Intiñan Solar Museum you can stand on the official equator, latitude 0-0-0 as measured by GPS. This outdoor museum features a demonstration where you see how water swirls down the drain depending on what side of the equator you’re standing on. If you are directly on it, it doesn’t swirl at all and goes straight down. Games and hands-on experiments make this a fun and educational outing.
Quito is at an elevation of 9,350 feet, which can be difficult to adjust to coming from the Arizona desert. We had just come from Cusco, Peru (11,000 feet), so Quito was actually easier for us.
Cusco is a great way station on the way to Machu Picchu. You can catch a train, start the hiking trail or just get acclimated. We spent our few days there visiting the market. It is the size of a football field and divided into rows of similar products. A few rows before you get to the seafood, you’ll start smelling it. Merchants smile and hand out samples.
We happily tasted our way through the fruit, nut and cheese rows but passed on the seafood aisle — neither my husband Mike or I could guess at some of the items for sale.
AZCENTRAL
Bhutan trip: A 50th birthday dream come true
If looking at unknown sea creatures writhing around makes you queasy, then the perfect antidote is the excellent chocolate museum. A free tour and demonstrations of all the products you can derive from Cacao culminates in the tasting room.
The last little treat we enjoyed in Cuzco was a visit to a llama sanctuary. We literally stumbled upon it near the main square. The non-profit organization takes in llamas and alpacas that people can’t care for and educates tourists about their plight all on small donations.
From Cuzco we journeyed on to the small town of Aguas Calientes for the final part of our trip to the site of Machu Picchu. You can hike up or take a bus. The road is very steep and full of switch-backs and hiking will not leave you much energy for exploring the site. In addition to spending 2 full days at the site we decided to climb La Montana, which is taller that the more famous Huayna Picchu but far less treacherous and gives you a fantastic view over the entire site.
All in all we had a wonderful time in Peru and Ecuador and can’t wait to go back.
The writer lives in Chandler.
